{"key":"post-16062993","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>16062993</id>\n<content>Acceptable for what?&amp;nbsp; If you're making an outdoor bed, you want a combination of sawdust, chips and bark.&amp;nbsp; If you're planning an indoor grow, mulch should be great.&amp;nbsp; I grind all my chips into mulch with my shredder.&amp;nbsp; Chips themselves tend to poke holes in the filter patch bags, so I quit using them at all for indoor grows.&amp;nbsp; I only use sawdust and shredded bark.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Also, it doesn't have to be hardwood for most species.&amp;nbsp; Well aged pine works, but be sure to spread the sawdust out in the sun for a full summer before use. I use Douglas fir sawdust/bark for our &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Mountain-Mushroom-Farm&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;commercial shiitake farm&lt;/a&gt;, not hardwood.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>16067543</next>\n<prev>16062196</prev>\n<first>16062078</first>\n<last>16067543</last>\n<when>1333942610</when>\n<utime>04/09/12 06:36 AM</utime>\n</post>"}